#Analysis of WannaMine (Overpass-the-Hash) via Kerberos Downgrade
##Overview:

This exercise involves detecting a Kerberos encryption type downgrade, a common indicator of the Overpass-the-Hash technique used by the WannaMine cryptojacking worm. The goal is to configure a Snort/Suricata rule that triggers when a weak encryption type is requested.
Prerequisites

    Environment: Linux (HTB Student Lab)

    Tools: Snort , grep, nano

    PCAP Source: /home/htb-student/pcaps/wannamine.pcap

    Rule File: /etc/snort/rules/local.rules (or equivalent)

###Technical Context

When an attacker performs Overpass-the-Hash, they often force the Kerberos authentication process to use RC4-HMAC (Type 23) instead of more secure types like AES-256. This is because the RC4-HMAC subkey is derived directly from the user's NT hash.
Rule Configuration

To trigger an alert on this traffic, the local.rules file must contain a rule targeting the Kerberos etype field.

###The Rule:
Code snippet

alert tcp any any -> any 88 (msg:"Kerberos Encryption Type Downgrade (RC4-HMAC)"; content:"|a1|"; depth:40; content:"|02 01 17|"; distance:0; sid:1000001; rev:1;)

Note: 17 in hex represents the decimal value 23.
Execution & Verification

Run the engine against the PCAP to verify the rule triggers:
Bash

snort -r /home/htb-student/pcaps/wannamine.pcap -c /etc/snort/rules/local.rules

###Conclusion
The answer of the given question is 17. If we enter this value at XX this will create an alert.


#Analysis of Neutrino Gootkit Traffic via Zeek
##Overview

This document details the process of analyzing network traffic associated with the Neutrino Exploit Kit and Gootkit malware. By processing the packet capture with Zeek, we extract certificate metadata to identify specific network signatures and indicators of compromise (IoCs).
Prerequisites

    Environment: Linux / Parrot OS (HTB Student Lab)

    Tools: Zeek, grep, standard Linux command-line utilities

    Data Source: /home/htb-student/pcaps/neutrinogootkit.pcap

##Execution Steps
1. Generate Network Logs

Run Zeek against the targeted PCAP file using the /usr/local/zeek/bin/zeek binary. The -C flag is utilized to ignore checksum errors common in malicious or altered packet captures:
Bash

sudo /usr/local/zeek/bin/zeek -C -r /home/htb-student/pcaps/neutrinogootkit.pcap

2. Search for the Certificate Trace

Zeek automatically extracts X.509 certificate metadata into a structured log file named x509.log. Use grep to filter this log file for the specific organizational signature "MyCompany Ltd.":
Bash

cat x509.log | grep "MyCompany Ltd."

